data.content:
Yes — **MSTest v3.3+** supports a generic `DynamicData<T>` attribute that works with tuples, giving you compile-time type safety:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData<(string, bool)>(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` — mismatched types are now a compile error
- `DynamicData` → `DynamicData<(string, bool)>` — the generic attribute binds the data source type
- Array literals `["x", true]` → tuple literals `("x", true)`

This requires the `MSTest.TestFramework` package **≥ 3.3**. The test method signature stays the same — MSTest automatically destructures the tuple into the method parameters.
